Recommendations

We reiterated in our previous years’ recommendation and the Management agreed that the Municipal Mayor:
Direct the Inventory Committee to fully conduct the physical count of all PPE and prepare and submit the RPCPPE to the Auditor not later than January 31 of the following year;
Require the GSO-Designate and Municipal Accountant to prepare, maintain and update the Property Cards (PC) and PPE Ledger Cards for all PPE accounts; and
Direct the Municipal Accountant to determine the specific details of the undepreciated PPEs and recognize depreciation expense for all depreciable PPE items;
We further recommended and the Management agreed that the Municipality avail of the one-time cleansing of PPE accounts as provided under COA Circular No. 2020-006 to finally establish PPE balances that are verifiable as to existence, condition and accountability.

Henceforth, we recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the:
a. Petty Cash Custodian to return to the Treasurer the unused petty cash at the close of the year to give way for the set up of a new cash advance for Petty Cash in the ensuing year;
b. Petty Cash Custodian to exercise control and adhere to the documentary requirements in the disbursement and replenishment of Petty Cash. Ensure that PCV is prepared and duly approved by signed/approved prior to spending and that a Summary of PCVs and Petty Cash Replenishment Report are prepared during the replenishment process;
c. Petty Cash Custodian and Municipal Accountant to stop the practice of charging inappropriate expenses against the Petty Cash Fund. Instead, incorporate in the annual procurement plan all supplies and materials regularly purchased by the Municipality and refrain from using the PCF in paying payable accounts;
d. Municipal Accountant to rectify the entry upon replenishment by debiting the appropriate expense account and the crediting the Cash in Bank, Local Currency Current Account (LCCA) instead of Petty Cash following the provisions of the New Government Accounting System (NGAS) Manual. Make sure that disbursement vouchers are supported with complete documentation before processing any claims against government funds.

Based on the foregoing, we recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the Municipal Treasurer, Municipal Accountant, Municipal Disaster Risk Reduction and Management Officer (MDRRMO) and Bids and Awards Committee (BAC) to:
a. submit a valid explanation on why the procurement of goods charged against the P5.0 million cash donation from the Office of the President failed to pass through the proper mode of procurement and incurrence of ineligible expenses charged against the fund;
b. for further evaluation of the Audit Team, cause submission of the lacking reports supporting the liquidation reports;
c. Municipal Treasurer to stop the practice of procuring goods from cash advances, except for petty cash expenses in accordance with applicable laws, rules and regulations;
d. BAC to strictly adhere to the provisions of 2016 RIRR of R.A. No. 9184 on the use of the alternative mode of procurement, if competitive bidding is not viable;
e. MDRRMO, in the event of an emergency or such like disaster, to assess and prepare the necessary supplemental plan, and thereafter request for the purchase of the needed goods/services upon approval of the Head of Procuring Entity (HoPE) and of the Local Sanggunian, if warranted in order to prevent piecemeal procurement; and
f. Municipal Accountant to ensure the completeness of documents supporting the disbursement vouchers before making any payment.

We recommended that the Municipal Mayor require the:
a. BAC, MGSO, and the Municipal Accountant to:
i. submit a valid explanation relative to the insufficiency of information provided in some documents and the absence of other supporting documents;
ii. submit the lacking documentary requirements to the Audit Team for further evaluation of the transactions pursuant to Section 4(6) of P.D. No. 1445;
b. Municipal Accountant to ensure completeness of supporting documents accompanying the disbursement vouchers before making any payment; and
c. BAC to comply with the posting and reporting requirements of the GPPB Circular 01-2020 for information purposes and transparency.

We recommended the following:

a. The Municipal Mayor to direct the concerned Municipal officials and employees to liquidate and/or refund immediately their unused cash advances pursuant to the provisions of Section 339 of RA No. 7160 and Section 89 of PD No. 1445, to avoid accumulation of unliquidated cash advances and to attain a fair presentation of the relevant accounts in the financial statements;  

b. The Municipal Accountant to adhere to pertinent provisions and ensure that no cash advances shall be allowed to any official or employee unless the previous cash advance granted is settled or a proper accounting thereof is made;

c. The Municipal Mayor to direct the imposition of appropriate sanctions for the unjustified failure of the concerned Municipal officials and employees to liquidate their cash advances; and



d. The Municipal Mayor to direct the concerned Municipal officials to follow the guidelines and procedures set in COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016 on the write-off, if warranted, of the unliquidated cash advances which have been long outstanding/remained dormant in the books of accounts.

We recommended the following:

a. The Local Chief Executive (LCE) to direct the concerned Municipal officials and employees to liquidate and/or refund immediately their unused cash advances pursuant to the provisions of Section 339 of RA No. 7160 and Section 89 of PD No. 1445, to avoid accumulation of unliquidated cash advances and to attain a fair presentation of the relevant accounts in the financial statements;  

b. The Municipal Accountant to adhere to pertinent provisions and ensure that no cash advances shall be allowed to any official or employee unless the previous cash advance granted is settled or a proper accounting thereof is made;




c. The LCE to direct the imposition of appropriate sanctions for the unjustified failure of the concerned Municipal officials and employees to liquidate their cash advances; and







d. The LCE to direct the concerned Municipal officials to follow the guidelines and procedures set in COA Circular No. 2016-005 dated December 19, 2016 on the write-off, if warranted, of the unliquidated cash advances which have been long outstanding/remained dormant in the books of accounts.

We recommended that the Local Chief Executive direct the Municipal Accountant to:

a. Make necessary adjusting entries for the improper recognition of the fund transfers, and properly record subsequent releases in the books of the Municipality to reflect correct balances in the financial statements;

b. Ensure that all required documents such as the Memorandum of Agreement, Approved Estimated Expenses, Official Receipt, etc. are accomplished and attached to the Disbursement Vouchers prior to the release of funds;

c.  Monitor the utilization of the funds released to the implementing agencies by requiring submission of liquidation reports; and

d. Require refund of the unexpended balance of the fund transfer, if any, evidenced by an Official Receipt.

We recommended that the management consider the following:
a. The need of each Office/ Department for the estimated number of JOs to be hired;
b. The qualification standard so they will be assigned to the Office/Department where
their service were most needed or where they are most suited;
c. Ensure that the JO personnel are identified to specific projects which should indicate
the Project Title, and
d. The wage rate should be in accordance with minimum wage rate;
e. Ensure that the hiring of JO personnel be in accordance with Section 77 Of RA 7160
and CSC Memorandum Circular No. 17, series of 2002.
